This is a great rifle which I'll be happy to keep. I'm just curious what I'd be missing.

title: For Sale:  PRICE REDUCED - $700 OBO - Musket composed of US Model 1816 stock and parts from other antique guns
postcontent:
REDUCED - $700 OBO

I am selling a musket that is composed of parts from different guns.  A local dealer here in Tucson has identified the stock as that of a US Model 1816 Musket.   The other parts are more mysterious.  Here is the descriptive information on those parts:

Barrel: The barrel is .69 caliber, so I am guessing that it is early American (or perhaps French) rather than British.  It is 42.5 inches long with the tang (40.25 inches without).  Someone belled out the barrel at some point, however, and I do not know whether the length was altered when that was done.  The barrel is round and smooth-bore.  (There are some faint lines inside the barrel, but they do not appear to be rifling.)  The barrel has the initials "N J" on the side opposite the lock. On the bottom, I found the marks "6⁰ N 10" grouped together at one spot, and the single letter "S" at another spot. The barrel has a production year on top, in the breech area. It appears to be 1801, but the third digit in the year is gouged and difficult to read. A little farther forward on the top of the barrel, I found some initials, but they are very difficult to read. I think the initials consist of one or two letters followed by “& P” (or maybe “& D”).

Lock: The lock is a would-be Tower lock.  It has the word "Tower" and the crown in the right places, but lacks the year and the monarch's initials. Inside, it appears to have the letter “D” on the mainspring.  I have read that a lot of imported English locks with imitation Tower markings were sold in America the early 19th Century.

Ramrod: The ramrod, which appears to be from yet another gun, has the numbers “5 5” and small crown on it.

Other information:  The musket is from the New York area, and the “N J” on the barrel may refer to New Jersey.  The stock has the words “1827 US” hand-carved on it.

I have sought help in identifying the parts by posting the above information and pictures of the musket on a few different forums.  I have received a lot of different opinions and helpful information, but nothing definitive.

My best guess is that an early American gunsmith or militiaman or hunter assembled this musket from spare parts in 1827 or earlier.  This is only a guess, however, so use your own judgment.

Price: $700 or best offer.  All reasonable offers considered.

In addition to the two pictures here, I have posted a lot of detailed pictures of the musket at Photobucket:  
http://s1194.photobucket.com/user/mothermarysanto/library/Musket%20Unknown?sort=3&evt=email_share&page=1

title: For Sale:  SC Concealed Carry Course
postcontent:
SC Concealed Weapons Permit Course, Saturday Feb 8th 2014, from 9am to 6pm hosted by Living Way Community Church 3239 N Highway 101, Greer, SC, 29651. Course cost $50. You need to bring your firearm, 50 rounds of ammo, and a belt with holster. any questions feel free to call me at REDACTED or go to facebook and add Blue Ridge Firearms Training. SEE COMMENTS BELOW. Register online at 
WWW.BLUERIDGEFIREARMSTRAINING.COM
Course Requirements

#1. Absolutely no charges/convictions for any Felonies, Criminal Domestic Violence, Drugs, or any misdemeanors that carry more than 2+ years imprisonment / probation or any charge that would prohibit you from owning or possessing a firearm. If found NOT GUILTY you should still be eligible. If you
are unsure about your status you can contact SLED at REDACTED for clarification.

#2. All necessary paperwork will be provided by me. Make sure that the address on your SC drivers license matches your current address. If not SLED will send the application back.

#3. Wear a tight neck shirt, no collared shirts please. Also bring a ball cap guys and girls. All other protective gear (safety glasses and hearing protection) will be provided by me. If you want to bring your own protective gear that is fine as well.

#4. Have a holster with at least 1 level of retention. This means a type of holster with a strap, snap, or button that secures the handgun from being pulled from the holster without being unsecured first. Wear long pants with a belt please. 

#5. Bring a small to medium caliber handgun with 50 rounds of ammunition, .22 cal, .32cal, .380cal, .38cal, 9mm, .40cal, 10mm, .45cal. No magnum high caliber pistols please. If you do not currently own a firearm, speak with me prior to the class and arrangements can be made to borrow one. You will still be responsible for the ammo for the borrowed firearm.

#6. The total cost of the course is $100. This needs to be separated as such, $50. cash for the instructor, and a $50. cashiers check or money order made out to SLED. You do not have to have the SLED fee the day of the class, only when you get ready to mail the application off. The course is 8 hours mandatory per state law, no exceptions.

Most important is safety, Know your firearm prior to class, if you need to practice to familiarize yourself with your firearm or to schedule a class, call me at REDACTED.
